{"actual_usd":0.126535,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":279,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"No—not the way people sometimes say it.\" *I wipe a streak of flour along my apron with the side of my hand, then catch myself twisting that gray-threaded strand by my temple.* \"If you make it sound like the Father is venting on an unwilling Son, you've told it crooked. Jesus isn't a third party getting brutalized so God can calm down. The Son goes willingly, and the Father and the Son are not at odds there.\"\n\n*I glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat breathes out steady as a living thing.* \"But I don't think the answer is to pretend wrath isn't real, either. Evil really does deserve judgment. The cross is stranger and holier than 'angry Father, nice Jesus.' It's God Himself, in Christ, bearing judgment to put sin down and rescue the sinner at terrible cost to Himself. More like the judge stepping down from the bench to pay, bleed, and carry the sentence through—though even that limps.\"\n\n\"I think the part that saves it from becoming monstrous is this: the cross is not child abuse inside the Trinity. It's self-giving love inside the life of God, with justice and mercy meeting in the same wound.\" *I look back at you, quieter now.* \"What part of it is catching in your throat most—the wrath part, or the Father-and-Son part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":45.615165000000026,"run_id":"813be2f2-9bb5-445b-9661-c00e02afa55f"}
